Try this delicious apple cranberry pie recipe by Chef Maya-Camille Broussard of @justiceofthepies! 🍏🥧

Ingredients:
3-4 rolls of pre-made crust OR your favorite pie crust recipe
6 Granny Smith Apples (4-4 1/2 cups)
4 TBSP unsalted butter
1 cup light brown sugar
1/2 cup granulated sugar
1/4 cup all-purpose, unbleached flour 
1 1/2 tsp ground cinnamon
1/2 tsp ground nutmeg
1 cup cranberry sauce (with whole berries)
1 large egg plus 1 TBSP water for egg wash
All-purpose, unbleached flour for dusting.

Instructions
1. Preheat oven to 350°
2. Peel, core and slice the apples.
3. In a large heavy-bottomed pot, melt the butter on medium heat
4. In a large bowl, combine the apples, sugar, flour and seasonings until the apples are well coated with the dry ingredients.
5. Pour the contents of the bowl in to the pot with the melted butter and stir, while allowing the butter to macerate with the flour mixture and the apples. If your mixture starts to stick to the pot as it heats up, feel free to add a little bit of water (no more than 1/8th cup).
6. Fold in cranberry sauce, turn off the heat and allow the apples to cool.
7. Line a 9” pie plate with pie crust. 
8. Using “crust” cutters, cut out shapes for the top of the pie. Set side. 
9. Place apple filling into the crust-lined pie plate. 
10. Place first layer of crust cut-outs onto the outer perimeter of the pie. Before placing another later of crust cut-outs on top of that, lightly brush an egg wash onto the first layer (and every subsequent layer.) This helps the crust cut outs to stick to each other. 
11. Place on a baking sheet and place in the oven for 35-45 minutes or until the pie has baked to a beautiful, golden brown color. 
12. Allow the pie to cool for 10-15 minutes before enjoying!

We're excited to share these tasty tiny tarts by @foodieinnewyork! 

Your favorite pie dough, rolled to 1/4-inch thickness, or two store-bought pie dough rounds
1 (8-ounce) package of full fat cream cheese, cold
3/4 cup heavy whipping cream, cold
1/2 cup powdered sugar
1 teaspoon vanilla extract (optional)
Assorted fresh fruit (I used fresh cherries and raspberries)
1. Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Roll the dough to 1/4-inch thickness. Cut out 6 (6-inch) rounds of dough and carefully fit them into the mini tart pans. Freeze for 10 minutes.
2. Prick the bottom of the crust with a fork all over, then line the bottom with foil or parchment paper, and something to weight the crust down (dried beans or pie weights). Bake for 15 minutes, until the crust starts to dry out. Remove the beans or weights, and bake another 5-10 minutes, just until it’s cooked through and a light, golden color.
3. Remove from the oven and let cool on a cooling rack completely (a warm crust will melt the filling).
4. Once the crust has cooled completely to room temperature, make the filling. Place the cold cream cheese, cold heavy cream, powdered sugar and vanilla in a large bowl. Use an electric mixer to beat until very stiff peaks forms, and the filling smooths out (initially, it may be a little lumpy from the cold cream cheese, but if you keep beating, it will smooth out). You want the filling to really thicken up.
5. Once the filling is thick, spread it evenly into your already-baked tart crusts. Save about 1 cup of filling, which you will use to pipe designs on top.
6. Top with fresh fruit, keeping some whole and cutting some in half to expose the inside beauty of the fruit. 
7. Transfer the remaining filling to a piping bag fitted with a 2D tip. Pipe designs over the top of each of the tarts. (If the filling has warmed up, transfer it to the refrigerator until it stiffens up so that it can be piped.) 
8. These are best enjoyed the day they’re made. Serve cold. 

#wiltoncakes #minitarts #fruit

Having food allergies as a child did not stop Adrienne Smith of @adriennesclassicdesserts from baking, but instead led her to find alternative ways to make healthier desserts. Read more below about her mission to show everyone that there are healthier food alternatives that taste good!
.
“My love for baking began at an early age while watching my father bake in our family's kitchen. He made the absolute best pound cake, and it always made our kitchen smell like an old fashion bakery. He is health-conscious, which led me to embrace a healthy lifestyle and incorporate healthier ingredients in my baking. As a child, I had several food allergies, so when I started baking, I began experimenting with alternative ingredients. That gave me the passion to come up with finding alternatives for others who may also have food allergies.
.
Baking for me originally revolved around entertaining my family and friends at dinners, cookouts, and other gatherings that involved food.  Some family members had certain conditions like diabetes or food allergies. This inspired me to create healthy baked goods that look and taste great, have all natural ingredients, and can be eaten by anyone.
.
I am most proud of getting my sugar free Carrot Ginger Layer Cake into Whole Foods Market.  Since it was my very first sugar free baked good, getting it approved for retail sale at Whole Foods Market sort of validated that I was on the right track. I will never forget walking into that first Whole Foods store and seeing my cake in the freezer section. Also, the times that I conducted food demos and tastings and watched people's reactions when they realized that the sample they had just tasted was actually sugar free!” 
.
Don’t forget to check out @adriennesclassicdesserts for some delectable desserts!
